{
  "family": "Fries-, Photo-Fries, and Anionic Ortho-Fries Rearrangement",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(=O)c1ccccc1O"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "Cl[Al](Cl)Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "The Fries rearrangement of phenyl acetate to 2-hydroxyacetophenone is a classic, simple, and unambiguous textbook example. It clearly demonstrates the core transformation: the migration of an acyl group from a phenolic oxygen to an ortho position on the aromatic ring, catalyzed by a Lewis acid (AlCl3). The reactants and products are small, acyclic where possible, and easily parsed, making it an ideal canonical seed.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses the simplest possible phenyl ester (phenyl acetate) to avoid complex aromatic systems that could overlap with other named reactions involving arenes. The transformation is a specific acyl migration, distinct from Claisen (allyl migration), Fischer-Hepp (nitrosamine migration), or general electrophilic aromatic substitution reactions like Friedel-Crafts acylation, as the acyl group originates from the substrate itself."
  }
}
